First of all, we need to find out the clean mean for each child, clean mean indicates we should remove the score from cheater teacher, after gain the clean mean, we are going to calculate the residual from honest teacher, and aggregate all children together to get the \(\mu_2\) and \(\sigma_2\)

ML.func <- function(dat, m2, s2, startvec){
  y <- dat[,1] %>% pull()
  objective.func <- function(pars){
    p <- pars[1]
    m1 <- pars[2]
    s1 <- pars[3]
    sumlikelihood <- sum(-log(p * dnorm(y, m1, s1) + (1-p) * dnorm(y, m2, s2)))
    if(is.na(sumlikelihood) | is.infinite(sumlikelihood) | is.nan(sumlikelihood))
      sumlikelihood <- (abs(p) + abs(m1) + abs(s1)) * 1e+10
    return(
      sumlikelihood
    )
  }
  maximumlikelihood.fit <- nlm(f=objective.func, p=startvec)
  return(maximumlikelihood.fit)
}
ML.func(ss,s$mean,s$sd,c(1,1,5))

Secondly, we need to aggregate all children which from cheater teacher. Since the \(\mu_2\) and \(\sigma_2\) is known, we can easily substitute into maximum likelihood function to obtain the estimated proportion, \(\mu_1\) and \(\sigma_1\), the object function we used in maximum likelihood function is sum(-log(\(P\times dnorm(Y_i,\mu_2,\sigma_2)+(1-P)\times dnorm(Y_i,\mu_1,\sigma_1)\))). Consequently, we obtain that the proportion is around 23.3%, the \(\mu_1\) is around 7.44 and the \(\sigma_1)\) is around 3.14.
